\begin_layout Subsection
Endogenous price
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In our base model we assumed that the price is set by the larger outside
 market.
 In this section we consider other scenarios of price setting: competitive
 price and price set by the intermediary.
 Main results of this section are: 1) there is a continuum of competitive
 price equilibria; 2) characterization of #matches-maximizing pricing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We adjust our notation a little bit to account for the fact that demand
 depends on price.
 Namely, buyer arrival rate is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta(\alpha,p),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\beta(0,p)=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{\alpha}>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{p}<0$
\end_inset

.
 The assumption I am making here is that buyer arrival rate responds to
 the changes in platform policies only through the average acceptance rate
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and price 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Let buyer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's expected acceptance rate for his job be 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

, the expected match value conditional on being matched be 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Additionally, buyer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 has hassle cost 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 from using the platform.
 If the buyer does not use the platform he gets payoff of zero.
 If he uses the platform he experiences a disutility of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 After requesting a service, if he is accepted, he pays price 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and gets payoff of 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, buyer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 joins iff 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha_{i}(v_{i}-p)-f_{i}\geqslant0.
\]

\end_inset

As defined above, the average acceptance rate across buyers is 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 The assumption is that 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mbox{\#potential buyers}]\cdot\Pr(\alpha_{i}(v_{i}-p)-f_{i}\geq0)=\beta(\alpha,p)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

Denote demand elasticities wrt 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and wrt 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\eps_{\alpha}=\frac{\beta_{\alpha}\alpha}{\beta}>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eps_{p}=-\frac{\beta_{p}p}{\beta}>0$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Price set by the intermediary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In this section we study a situation when the platform controls the price
 on the platform (e.g.
 in case of Uber and Instacart).
 This brings us closer to the literature on pricing in two-sided markets
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "RT06,Wey10"

\end_inset

).
 However, unlike these papers, we are more specific about where the network
 effect is coming from and also sellers have a decision margin not related
 to participation – acceptance rate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Match-maximizing platform.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
From the previous section we know that whatever price a Walrasian auctioneer
 picks, it can be sustained in a competitive equilibrium.
 We thus pose a question: if the platform can set the price, what price
 and disclosure policy should it use to maximize the number of matches?
 The platform solves 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\max_{\lambda,p}\alpha\beta(\alpha,p),
\]

\end_inset

subject to {
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:V-via-pi"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:pi(c)"

\end_inset

}.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We know from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "prop:Pareto-frontier"

\end_inset

 the form of the optimal disclosure policy for given price.
 How should the price be set? To induce more demand, the platform would
 like to choose lower price.
 But the lower the price, the lower seller utilization rate can be implemented.
 The next result quantifies this tradeoff.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:opt-price-and-conflation-max-m"

\end_inset

Assume sellers have no private information.
 The #matches-maximizing disclosure policy has the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\lambda}(x)=\begin{cases}
\Exp[x|x\leq mc], & \alpha\\
\Exp[x|x>mc], & 1-\alpha
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $mc$
\end_inset

 solve the system of equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\Exp[x|x\leq mc] & = & p\nonumber \\
F(mc) & = & \alpha\nonumber \\
\frac{\eps_{\alpha}+1}{\eps_{p}} & = & \frac{mc-p}{p}\label{eq:opt-price-via-elasticities}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The proof is the Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vpageref
reference "proof:prop:confl-and-price"

\end_inset

.
 From 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:opt-price-via-elasticities"

\end_inset

 note that 
\begin_inset Formula $mc>p$
\end_inset

, which is indication of the platform taking into account network effects,
 namely the demand expansion for higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Compare it to the benchmark when the monopolist sets the price.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Revenue-maximizing platform.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
When the platform in the stage of growth, it wants to be bigger.
 Later on, the platform turn to monetization.
 We are interested in answering the following question: How does the platform
 policies change when it is profit-maximizing? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To get a cut from sellers revenue, the platform uses two prices: price 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 for buyers and wage 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 for sellers.
 Additionally, it has disclosure policy as an instrument.
 The platform's objective is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
 &  & \max_{\lambda,p,w}\beta(\alpha,p)\alpha(p-w)\\
 & \mbox{s.t.} & AC(\alpha)\leq w
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and subject to {
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:V-via-pi"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:pi(c)"

\end_inset

}.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:opt-price-and-conflation-max-rent"

\end_inset

Assume sellers have no private information.
 The profit-maximizing disclosure policy has the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\lambda}(x)=\begin{cases}
\Exp[x|x\leq mc], & \alpha\\
\Exp[x|x>mc], & 1-\alpha
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $mc$
\end_inset

 solve the system of equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Exp[x|x\leq mc] & = & w\\
F(mc) & = & \alpha\\
\frac{1}{\eps_{p}} & = & \frac{p-w}{p}\\
\frac{\eps_{\alpha}+1}{\eps_{p}} & = & \frac{mc-w}{p}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The next results states how the marketplace variables change after the platform
 transitions from the match-maximizing mode to the revenue-maximizing mode.
 Imagine the platform starts with match-maximizing as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:opt-price-and-conflation-max-m"

\end_inset

.
 It makes zero revenue there because it takes zero fee on transactions.
 There are two ways to increase the intermediary's revenue.
 One is increase buy price, the other one is to decrease the wage.
 However, decreasing 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 decreases acceptance rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, so it might be profitable to increase both 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
 Depending on the properties of the demand, the platform may find it optimal
 either to increase both 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

, or decrease both 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

, or increase 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and decrease 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
 The next result provides sufficient conditions for when the acceptance
 rate is higher (lower) under profit-maximization than under match-maximization.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Conjecture
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{p}+\alpha\beta_{\alpha p}>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{pp}>0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{PM}<\alpha^{MM}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w^{PM}<p^{MM}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{pp}<0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{\alpha p}<0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{PM}>\alpha^{MM}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w^{PM}>p^{MM}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


